 Board Game Framework
A modular, extensible C# framework designed for turn-based board games. This project implements advanced Design Patterns to ensure a clear separation between game logic, user interface, and artificial intelligence.

Architectural Overview
This framework is built using a Layered Architecture to satisfy Master's level software engineering requirements.

1. Core Board Hierarchy
We use a "Contract-Template-Implementation" model to ensure that adding new games (like Gomoku or Notakto) requires minimal code changes.

IBoard: The interface defining the mandatory capabilities of any game board.

BaseBoard: An abstract class containing shared logic for grid management, cell validation, and move placement.

GomokuBoard / NotaktoBoard: Specific implementations that define unique win conditions and board dimensions.

2. Command Pattern (Undo/Redo System)
To handle the requirement for move history and "Undo" functionality, we implemented the Command Design Pattern.

ICommand & MoveCommand: Encapsulates every action as an object.

CommandManager: Manages the stack of executed commands.

HistoryManager & GameSaver: Provides persistence and tracking of the game state.

3. Strategy Pattern (Pluggable AI)
The AI system is completely decoupled from the Player classes, allowing for "hot-swappable" difficulty levels and game-specific logic.

IComputerStrategy: The common interface for all AI "brains."

ComputerMoveLogic: A base win-scanning engine that provides generic "look-ahead" capabilities.

RandomStrategy: A baseline AI for testing and "Easy" mode.

NumericalTicTacToeStrategy: A specialized AI that handles the specific mathematical parity and Sum rules.

Getting Started
Prerequisites
Visual Studio 2022 (v17.10 or later)

.NET 6.0 or 8.0 SDK

How to Add a New Game
Create a Board: Inherit from BaseBoard and override CheckWin.

Create a Game: Inherit from Game and define the starting parameters.

Register in Factory: Add the new game type to GameFactory.cs so it appears in the main menu.

 Design Patterns Used
Factory Method: Centralized object creation in GameFactory.

Strategy: Decoupled AI algorithms via IComputerStrategy.

Command: Robust Undo/Redo via MoveCommand.

Singleton/Manager: Centralized history tracking via CommandManager.

Observer (UI): Decoupling logic from the ConsoleDisplay via IDisplay
